#  Day 58 – Task A-2: Developing the Security Assessment Plan | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## From Assessor Selection to Assessment Planning

Day 57 selected the assessor — an external healthcare-focused security assessment firm with AWS competency and NIST 800-53A assessment methodology experience. Task A-2 produces the Security Assessment Plan (SAP): the formal document that defines what will be assessed, how each control will be evaluated, what evidence will be collected, what the rules of engagement are, and what the assessment team will deliver.

The SAP is not a formality — it is a contract between the assessor and the system owner that sets expectations, prevents misunderstandings, and protects both parties. A well-developed SAP enables the assessor to conduct a focused, efficient evaluation. A poorly developed SAP produces an assessment that is either too shallow (misses important controls) or too broad (spends time on controls that do not warrant deep investigation), and creates disputes at the end when the deliverables do not match expectations.

For OpenMRS at MyClinic, the SAP needs to be calibrated to a High-impact system assessment — comprehensive enough to give the AO confidence that the authorization decision is based on a thorough evaluation, but scoped to the actual system boundary and control set without unnecessary scope creep.

---

## What I Worked On Today

NIST SP 800-37 Task A-2 requires the assessor to develop the security assessment plan based on the SSP and the assessment objectives. The SAP is reviewed and approved by the system owner and AO before assessment activities begin. Today I work through each component of the SAP for the OpenMRS assessment — scope, objectives, team and roles, schedule, assessment procedures for key control families, rules of engagement, and reporting requirements.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clarified SAP development today is understanding the relationship between the SAP and NIST SP 800-53A.

SP 800-53A is the companion document to SP 800-53 that defines the assessment procedures for each control. For every control in SP 800-53, SP 800-53A defines: the assessment objectives (what the assessor is trying to determine), and the assessment methods and objects (examine what documents, interview which roles, test what system behaviors).

The SAP does not rewrite SP 800-53A — it applies SP 800-53A to the specific OpenMRS system. For each control, the SAP specifies: which SP 800-53A assessment objects apply to this system (e.g., the OpenMRS authentication configuration, not a generic authentication system), which interview subjects are relevant (the ISSO and IT Administrator, not a generic "system administrator"), and what specific test scenarios are appropriate for this deployment (test TOTP MFA enforcement in the OpenMRS test environment, not generic MFA testing).

This tailoring is what makes the SAP useful rather than a boilerplate document. An assessor working from SP 800-53A without a tailored SAP would need to figure out the OpenMRS-specific assessment objects themselves — increasing assessment time and creating risk that important system-specific behaviors are missed. A well-developed SAP transfers that system knowledge from the ISSO to the assessor before testing begins.

