## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While developing the AC-3 role-based access control test procedures today, I came across details from the **2013 HIPAA Omnibus Rule implementation guidance** that HHS OCR published following a significant uptick in insider access abuse incidents.

OCR guidance specifically addressed the technical safeguard requirement for access controls — noting that organizations needed to demonstrate not just that roles existed in their EHR systems, but that role permissions were actually scoped to clinical need and that the controls were being tested. OCR had observed in its breach investigations that many healthcare organizations had role-based access control systems configured with overly broad permissions — essentially, clinical roles that could access any patient record regardless of care relationship.

The assessment test for AC-3 that I developed today — specifically, testing that an administrative staff account cannot access clinical encounter documentation, and that a clinician account cannot access system administration functions — directly addresses the gap pattern OCR identified. A security assessment that only examines the role configuration documentation without testing whether the role restrictions are actually enforced in practice would miss the implementation gap where roles are defined but not scoped.

This connects to the broader insight from today's SAP development: the test method in SP 800-53A is what distinguishes a security assessment from a document review. Examining the SSP tells the assessor what MyClinic claims the controls do. Testing the controls in the test environment tells the assessor whether they actually do it. Both methods are necessary; neither alone is sufficient for a High-impact system.

