## What I Am Still Thinking About

One aspect of the SAP I want to refine before it is finalized: the POA&M review procedure.

The SAP documents that the assessor will review POA&M items during the assessment — confirming that open items are accurately described and that compensating controls are in place. But I have not yet specified exactly how the assessor should document a POA&M finding that is more serious than described.

For example: if the CP-2 clinical downtime procedures POA&M item has a draft procedure document but it is substantially less developed than the POA&M entry implies, should the assessor document that as a new finding, an update to the existing POA&M item, or both?

My instinct is: the assessor documents their own assessment of the POA&M items' status and severity in the SAR, independent of how MyClinic has characterized them. If an item is characterized as "partially implemented with compensating controls" but the assessor finds that the compensating controls are inadequate, the SAR should reflect the assessor's independent evaluation — not defer to MyClinic's self-characterization. The AO should receive the assessor's view, not a confirmation of the system owner's view.

I want to add a specific section to the SAP addressing how the assessor handles POA&M items — documenting that their status assessment is independent and that discrepancies between MyClinic's POA&M characterization and the assessor's findings will be explicitly noted in the SAR.

